Supervised Learning - Foundations Project: ReCell¶

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

Buying and selling used phones and tablets used to be something that happened on a handful of online marketplace sites. But the used and refurbished device market has grown considerably over the past decade, and a new IDC (International Data Corporation) forecast predicts that the used phone market would be worth \$52.7bn by 2023 with a compound annual growth rate (CAGR) of 13.6% from 2018 to 2023. This growth can be attributed to an uptick in demand for used phones and tablets that offer considerable savings compared with new models.

Refurbished and used devices continue to provide cost-effective alternatives to both consumers and businesses that are looking to save money when purchasing one. There are plenty of other benefits associated with the used device market. Used and refurbished devices can be sold with warranties and can also be insured with proof of purchase. Third-party vendors/platforms, such as Verizon, Amazon, etc., provide attractive offers to customers for refurbished devices. Maximizing the longevity of devices through second-hand trade also reduces their environmental impact and helps in recycling and reducing waste. The impact of the COVID-19 outbreak may further boost this segment as consumers cut back on discretionary spending and buy phones and tablets only for immediate needs.

Objective¶

The rising potential of this comparatively under-the-radar market fuels the need for an ML-based solution to develop a dynamic pricing strategy for used and refurbished devices. ReCell, a startup aiming to tap the potential in this market, has hired you as a data scientist. They want you to analyze the data provided and build a linear regression model to predict the price of a used phone/tablet and identify factors that significantly influence it.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of used/refurbished phones and tablets. The data was collected in the year 2021. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

  • brand_name: Name of manufacturing brand
  • os: OS on which the device runs
  • screen_size: Size of the screen in cm
  • 4g: Whether 4G is available or not
  • 5g: Whether 5G is available or not
  • main_camera_mp: Resolution of the rear camera in megapixels
  • selfie_camera_mp: Resolution of the front camera in megapixels
  • int_memory: Amount of internal memory (ROM) in GB
  • ram: Amount of RAM in GB
  • battery: Energy capacity of the device battery in mAh
  • weight: Weight of the device in grams
  • release_year: Year when the device model was released
  • days_used: Number of days the used/refurbished device has been used
  • normalized_new_price: Normalized price of a new device of the same model in euros
  • normalized_used_price: Normalized price of the used/refurbished device in euros

To begin with, I observe that the recell has 3454 lines and 15 columns. Two of the columns, brand_name and os will probably be dropped because they contain too many categories for linear analysis. There are duplicate devices within the dataset, but this does not mean that there is duplicate information. Also, each device will not have exactly the same properties. One may be new, while another is used. The number of days a certain device was used may differ. What I also observce is that there are missing values that will have to be replaced. Some of the variables such as selfie_camera_mp, only have a few missing variables. Therfore, leaving them in place may not make a difference in the initial univatiate or bivariate analysis. However, main_camera_mp is missing 179 values. This must be addressed before any type of analysis. I will first replace the "nan: with NaN, which is recognized by Python, and then after copying the dataset, I will use the lambda function deecribed in the HandsOn Notebook to accomplish this. I will also need to replace the "yes" and "no" categories in 4g and 5g with nummbers and drop one of the variables to conduct the analysis. Then, I will convert the variables from category object to category int. That should be all I need to do before I conduct my linear analysis.

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)¶

  • EDA is an important part of any project involving data.
  • It is important to investigate and understand the data better before building a model with it.
  • A few questions have been mentioned below which will help you approach the analysis in the right manner and generate insights from the data.
  • A thorough analysis of the data, in addition to the questions mentioned below, should be done.

Questions:

  1. What does the distribution of normalized used device prices look like?
  2. What percentage of the used device market is dominated by Android devices?
  3. The amount of RAM is important for the smooth functioning of a device. How does the amount of RAM vary with the brand?
  4. A large battery often increases a device's weight, making it feel uncomfortable in the hands. How does the weight vary for phones and tablets offering large batteries (more than 4500 mAh)?
  5. Bigger screens are desirable for entertainment purposes as they offer a better viewing experience. How many phones and tablets are available across different brands with a screen size larger than 6 inches?
  6. A lot of devices nowadays offer great selfie cameras, allowing us to capture our favorite moments with loved ones. What is the distribution of devices offering greater than 8MP selfie cameras across brands?
  7. Which attributes are highly correlated with the normalized price of a used device?

For the purspose of this analysis, values above 0.06 with be considered nominally correlated and values above 0.80 to be highly correlated. There are high correlations between screen_size and battery (0.81) and screensize and weight (0.83). The relationship between battery size and weight is obvious. However, the relationship is not although this close correlation may indicate a case of colinerarity since the larger the battery, the heavier the device.

There is a nominal negative correlation between release year and 4g (-0.61). This makes sense because the older the phone, the less likely it is to have 4g capabilities.

There is a nominal correlation between selfie camera mp and release year (0.69). This likely indicates that the newer the phone, the greater the number of megapixels a camera will generate. There is also a nominal correlation between selfie camera mp and normalized used price. This likely indicates that the more megapixels per inch a device camera generates, the greater the resale value.

There is a nominal correlation between battery and weight (0.70), which we have already discussed. There is also a nominal correlation between battery and normalized used price. The longer the battery life, the greater the resale value.

There is a nominal negative correlation between realease year and days used (-0.75). That is becuase as the year of the phone increases, the number of days used possible decreases.

Finally, with regard to normalized used price, there is a nominal correlation with screen size (0.61). The larger the screensize, the more the resale price. There is also a strong correlation between normalized used and normalized new prices. This bodes well for the industry indicating that more expensive new devices will sell for higher prices than cheaper ones, also that devices hold their value over time (Code taken from FoodHub Project).

7. Variables correlated highly with¶

For the purpose of this analysis, nominal correlation is any number greater than 0.61 and high correlation is any number greater than 0.80. Three variables are correlated with normalized used price at a rate of 0.61. These are screen size, selfie camera mp and battery. All of these variables would make a used device more desirable. One variable is highly correlated with the normalized used price. That variable is normalized new price at a rate of 0.83. This suggests that a device will hold on to its value even when it enters the used market.

Create the lambda function to replace NaN with median values. The limit of this lambda function is that it must be applied every time I want to use it. Otherwise, the data will revert to its original state. I will apply it when I get ready to set up the train/test sets. This was not explained in the videos. I had to figure this out using trial and error.

Perform a train/test split using 30% of values for the test and 70% to train the model. Also, set the condition that each value will be selected randomly.

In [13]:
X_train,X_test,y_train,y_test=train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.30,random_state=1)

Now, we examine the four assumptions. The first is multicolinarity between variables. This is determined by calulating VIF (Variance Inflation Factor). VIF compared x variables to determine whether two or more are highly colinear. This means that the two variables may account for the same part of the phenomenon we hope to measure. If they are highly colinear, we should drop one of them.

3. Test for normality¶

Residuals should be normally distributed otherwise the confidence interval could become too wide or overfit or too narrow. To test for notmality, we first plot residuals using a hiostogram and a QQ plot and perform a visual inspection. Then, we perform a Shapiro-Wilks test to generate a p-value.

Histogram¶

In [ ]:
plt.figure(figsize=(5,5))
sns.histplot(recell_predict["Residules"],kde=True)
plt.show()

This distribution does not show a perfect normal distribution. Although it is somewhat skewed to the right with a long left tail, it is generally normally distributed.

QQ Plot¶

In [33]:
import pylab
import scipy.stats as stats
In [34]:
stats.probplot(recell_predict["Residules"],dist="norm",plot=pylab)
Out[34]:
((array([-3.44385758, -3.19630236, -3.05919064, ...,  3.05919064,
          3.19630236,  3.44385758]),
  array([-1.4984193 , -1.09797418, -0.98660319, ...,  0.91163355,
          0.92103776,  0.94353141])),
 (0.23359271417148778, 3.907103310161309e-15, 0.9864327295634032))

A visual inspection suggests that thise distribution tends toward normal.

Shapiro-Wilks Test¶

State the null and alternative hypothesis (Code to state null and alternative hypothesis taken from ENews Express project)

$H_o$: Residuals are normally distributed.

$H_a$: Residuals are NOT normally distributed.

In [35]:
stats.shapiro(recell_predict["Residules"])
Out[35]:
ShapiroResult(statistic=0.9738355875015259, pvalue=1.2527766699389244e-20)

Since p is significantly lower than 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis that the residuals are normally distributed strictly speaking. However, since visual inspection of other measures tends toward normal, we accept the conclusion of normalcy.

4.Homoscedascity versus Heteroscredascity¶

Is the variance of the residuals is symmetrical across the line of regression? A hetroscedastic pattern indicates the presence of outliers, which skew the results. A p-value genreated from the goldfledquandt test is used to make this determination.

Null and alternative hypptheses¶

$H_o$: The variance of the residuals is symmetrical accross the distribution.

$H_a$: The variance of the residuals is NOT symmetrical across the distribution.

In [36]:
import statsmodels.stats.api as sms
In [37]:
from statsmodels.compat import lzip
In [38]:
name=["F statistic","p-value"]
In [39]:
test=sms.het_goldfeldquandt(recell_predict["Residules"],X_train7)
In [40]:
lzip(name,test)
Out[40]:
[('F statistic', 1.0623060376284026), ('p-value', 0.14749079912843824)]

Since the p-value of 0.1475 is greater than 0.05, we fail to the null hypothesis that the distribution of the variance of reiduals is homoscedastic.

Conclusion¶

  1. Both train and test rmse are comparable at 0.24 each. Therefore, there is no indication of model overfitting.

  2. Results from MAE tests indicate that the final iteration, olsresidue_7, is able to predict normalized used prices within a mean error of 0.185 units using X_test2.

  3. Olsresidue_7 is both a good predictor of future normalized_used_price and also useful to make inferences about which variables influence normaized used price. Olsresidue_7 can explain 83.6% of normalized used price. The other 16.4% would be explained by vaiables that were not included in the model.

  4. The variable with the greatest impact on normalized used price was normalized new price. Of the 83.6% of normalized used price that can be explained by the olsresidue_7 model, 41% or 34% in total, can be explained by normalized used price. No other variable has close to that much influence on normalized used price although the closest is 4g_2 at -7.3% of 83.6 or -6% of the total. This suggsests that the best predictor of a used phone price is what the phone cost when it was new. Unfortunately, this model does not explain whether the price that is set means the phone will hold its value when it moves from the new to the used market or if it is what a consumer is actually willing to pay for a used phone. Actual cost was not a variable available in this data set.

  5. If this information were shared with a sales team in a final report, it would be helpful to understand the calculation that was set to detemine both noramlized new and used prices. The least expensive used phone I could find on the internet was $36. So, these two variables do not really explain actual prices such as the wholesale price business would pay to aquire devices or that a consumer would pay when they purchased a device in a retail setting.
